00:37:05.990 --> 00:37:08.330
that afterwards a little
bit more about what's

00:37:08.330 --> 00:37:10.274
actually going on
under the hood.

00:37:10.274 --> 00:37:12.440
AUDIENCE: I think I saw a
speedrun for "Half-Life 2"

00:37:12.440 --> 00:37:15.590
that worked by saving and
reloading the game so that when

00:37:15.590 --> 00:37:17.860
you reload the game, you're
in a different position.

00:37:17.860 --> 00:37:19.310
And the video for
those runs were

00:37:19.310 --> 00:37:21.740
edited so you can
only see the gameplay.

00:37:21.740 --> 00:37:24.320
Is that something that's
a specific category,

00:37:24.320 --> 00:37:26.300
as you mentioned the
categories before?

00:37:26.300 --> 00:37:29.060
ERIC KOZIEL: That would be
a segmented run for the most

00:37:29.060 --> 00:37:33.320
part, especially if they're
removing the in-between.

00:37:33.320 --> 00:37:37.370
But it really is up to
how the community defines

00:37:37.370 --> 00:37:41.510
what is challenging what
you're actually trying to show.

00:37:41.510 --> 00:37:44.930
And in this case, let's
say that Half-Life 2--

00:37:44.930 --> 00:37:47.150
simply by saving
and quitting is what

00:37:47.150 --> 00:37:49.070
actually alters your position.

00:37:49.070 --> 00:37:52.520
Then that's something that
you can use in what's called

00:37:52.520 --> 00:37:54.930
a "single-segment run,"
done in one sitting.

00:37:54.930 --> 00:37:59.450
But most often, for
those kinds of things,

00:37:59.450 --> 00:38:02.150
it's going to be segmented
in that you do a block of it,

00:38:02.150 --> 00:38:03.772
try to get it as
optimal as possible.

00:38:03.772 --> 00:38:05.480
In that save, you're
going to bring it up

00:38:05.480 --> 00:38:07.910
again and do another one.

00:38:07.910 --> 00:38:10.310
Whether or not it's
allowed or expected

00:38:10.310 --> 00:38:11.700
is really up to the game.

00:38:11.700 --> 00:38:13.580
And it really depends
on how the game

00:38:13.580 --> 00:38:16.000
interacts with those saves.

